'''Nagakura Shrine''' (ながくらじんじゃ) is a shrine in {{ill|lt=Karuizawa|Q1012064|qid=Q1012064|1=Karuizawa, Nagano}}, {{ill|lt=Kitasaku District|Q1142451|qid=Q1142451|1=Kitasaku District, Nagano}}, {{ill|lt=Nagano Prefecture|Q127877|qid=Q127877|1=Nagano Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}} listed in the ''{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}'', and under the {{ill|lt=modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|qid=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} its former rank was village shrine.

=== Enshrined deities ===
*{{ill|lt=Emperor Ōjin|Q317997|qid=Q317997|qid=Q317997|lt=Hondawake-no-Mikoto|1=Emperor Ōjin}}
*{{ill|lt=Empress Jingū|Q232803|qid=Q232803|lt=Okinagatarashi-hime-no-Mikoto|1=Empress Jingū}}
*{{ill|lt=Tamayorihime|Q56344982|qid=Q56344982|lt=Tamayori-hime|1=Tamayori-hime}}

=== History ===
It is located at the east end of {{ill|lt=Kutsukake-shuku|Q3200704|qid=Q3200704|1=Kutsukake-shuku}} on the {{ill|lt=Nakasendō|Q1154479|qid=Q1154479|1=Nakasendō}}, northeast of the {{ill|lt=Yukawa (Kitasaku District)|Q11563522|qid=Q11563522|lt=Yukawa River|1=Yugawa River}}. The founding date is unknown, but according to shrine tradition, around the {{ill|lt=Tenchō|Q1373138|qid=Q1373138|1=Tenchō}} era, when Nagakura post station on the old {{ill|lt=Tōsandō|Q1334011|qid=Q1334011|1=Tōsandō}} was developed, it was enshrined on Mount Nagakura, and the former site was called “Moto-Hachiman.” Kutsukake-shuku stood about 400 m south of the current site until its relocation after a fire in {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=An'ei|1=UNKNOWN}} 2 ({{ill|lt=1773|Q7692|qid=Q7692|1=1773}}), and Nagakura Shrine is presumed to have moved at the same time<ref name=A>Tanigawa (2000) p.224</ref>. The oldest stone structure in the precinct is a stone lantern from {{ill|lt=Kyōhō|Q1145048|qid=Q1145048|1=Kyōhō}} 16 ({{ill|lt=1731|Q6963|qid=Q6963|1=1731}}), comparatively recent, supporting relocation with the post-town move<ref name=A/>. There is also a poetry monument to Kutsukake Tokijirō by {{ill|lt=Shin Hasegawa|Q11653726|qid=Q11653726|1=Shin Hasegawa}}.

An alternative theory identifies Nagakura Suwa Shrine in Miyota, Miyota-machi (same district), where {{ill|lt=Oitai-shuku|Q3357559|qid=Q3357559|1=Otai-shuku}} was located, as the Shikinaisha “Nagakura Shrine”<ref>Nagano Prefecture Encyclopedia p.577</ref>.

